node.text:
🎧 SOUND ON: Timelapse of the James Webb Space Telescope

As the largest space telescope ever built, Webb must fold to fit into its rocket fairing for launch. Check out how the telescope is stowed into its launch configuration in this video! Once in space, Webb will unfold like a “Transformer” to show us the universe as we've never seen it before.

Having just completed testing, Webb is now being prepared to ship to its launch site of Kourou, French Guiana. 🚢

Music Credit: “Cotching” by Justin Black & Oscar Hill, Atmosphere Music Ltd. via Universal Production Music

#NASA #space #astronomy #universe #cosmos #tech #JWST #reels

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by NASA Webb Telescope on August 26, 2021.

node.text:
Testing complete ✅

The James Webb Space Telescope has completed its rigorous testing regimen at @NorthropGrumman, where it successfully demonstrated that it can survive launch conditions and a space environment. Now the engineering team is preparing to ship the observatory to its launch site of Kourou, French Guiana in South America.

This marks a major turning point for the mission. With integration and testing formally concluded for Webb, @NASA’s next giant leap into the cosmic unknown will soon be underway.

“After completing the final steps of the James Webb Space Telescope’s testing regimen, I can’t help but see the reflections of the thousands of individuals who have dedicated so much of their lives to Webb, every time I look at that beautiful gold mirror,” said Bill Ochs, Webb project manager for @NASAGoddard.

Read more at the link in our bio! Follow @NASAWebb to keep up with the latest updates.

Image credit: NASA/Chris Gunn

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by NASA Webb Telescope on August 25, 2021. May be an image of sky.

node.text:
Eighteen years ago today, the Spitzer Space Telescope began its mission to reveal the infrared universe to the world.

In one of the mission’s first released images, the spatial resolution and sensitivity of Spitzer at infrared wavelengths show a clear separation between the several key elements of Messier 81: the old stars, the interstellar dust heated by star formation activity, and the embedded sites of massive star formation.

The James Webb Space Telescope is an improved combination of the Hubble and Spitzer space telescopes—Hubble’s sensitivity and resolution, and Spitzer’s view of the infrared universe.

Image Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/S. Willner (Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics).

node.text:
Happy #WorldPhotographyDay! 📷

Over the years, our mission photographers have beautifully documented each stage of progress on the James Webb Space Telescope. We'd like to highlight the team and their work:

1. Taken by photographer Chris Gunn, this image shows Webb having just successfully completed a center of curvature test, an optical measurement of its primary mirror.

2. This group selfie of Webb engineers and technicians was taken by photographer Desiree Stover in the @NASAGoddard cleanroom.

3. NASA photographer Jolearra Tshiteya captured her fellow photographer Chris Gunn, who was in the process of taking an image of the Webb primary mirror.

4. Here, you can see one of the images that Chris Gunn took during the shoot in the previous photo. Engineers carefully examined the primary mirror ahead of installation of the instrument module.

5. In his Instagram takeover of our page, Chris Gunn named this photo as one of his favorites. You can check out more about his work process in the "Chris Gunn" Highlight on our profile.

#photo #camera #JamesWebbSpaceTelescope #NASA #selfie

node.text:
‼️ New @NASAJPL posters just dropped ‼️

The James Webb Space Telescope will collect light from more than 13.5 billion years ago. Building on the legacies of pioneers such as @NASAHubble, the Spitzer Space Telescope and more, it will also greatly expand our knowledge of planets around other stars. With its keen infrared vision, Webb will be powerful enough to search for molecules such as water vapor in exoplanet atmospheres.

Check out our Instagram Story to browse and download our full gallery of space telescope posters! These will continue to be available on our “Download ⬇️” Instagram highlight.

node.text:
One of Webb's first tasks will be to stare at a chunk of sky home to half a million galaxies! 👀

The size of three full Moons, this field will further what we know about the dawn of galaxy formation. Scientists will also search for rare, fully evolved galaxies that shut down star birth in the first 2 billion years after the Big Bang, and map how dark matter in galaxies has evolved with the galaxies' stellar content over the universe's lifetime.

Known as COSMOS-Webb, this is the largest project Webb will undertake during its first year. The COSMOS survey began in 2002 as a @NASAHubble program to image a much larger patch of sky, about the area of 10 full moons. From there, the collaboration snowballed to include most of the world's major telescopes on Earth and in space.

Read more at the link in our bio!

Credit: Jeyhan Kartaltepe (RIT); Caitlin Casey (UT Austin); and Anton Koekemoer (STScI), Alyssa Pagan (STScI).

#NASAWebb #galaxies #stars #universe #Hubble

node.text:
What does this image look like to you?

🐘  It may take some imagination to understand why this is known as the Elephant’s Trunk Nebula. Some might instead see a fleeing ghost or even a long-tailed betta fish.

🐘  This glowing stellar nursery is being sculpted by winds and radiation from a massive star located out of the field of view at left. This infrared image, courtesy of the Spitzer Space Telescope, gives a preview of what the James Webb Space Telescope will provide.

🐘  Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/W. Reach (SSC/Caltech)

🐘  #WorldElephantDay #Nebula #NASAWebb

Tag your original art, inspired by the James #Webb Space Telescope, on Twitter or Instagram with @NASAWebb or #JWSTArt, or email us at gsfc-nasawebb@mail.nasa.gov. For more info and rules, see: http://nasa.gov/jwstart
🎨
The James Webb Space Telescope – #NASA’s next infrared space observatory – will not only change what we know, but also how we think about the night sky and our place in the cosmos. This epic mission to look back in time at the first stars and galaxies has inspired artists from around the world to create art inspired by the mission. #spaceart #sciart  #STEAM #NASAWebb

node.text:
From vision ➡️ to reality

Swipe right to compare an early concept of the James Webb Space Telescope (then named the Next Generation Space Telescope) with the Webb telescope as it is today.

Before the Hubble Space Telescope was even launched, scientists and engineers were already asking the question — what’s next?

You'll notice that early designs of Webb don’t look too different from the completed version of the telescope now, incorporating a segmented mirror, an “open” design, and a large sunshield.

Credit: [1] NASA; [2] NASA/Chris Gunn

node.text:
Don’t let the serene, calming nature of NGC 891 fool you. Within its churning layers of gas and dust—and outflows bursting from the galaxy’s central plane—lie intense pockets of star formation. ✨

That’s why the James Webb Space Telescope researchers are planning to use the telescope’s unmatched sensitivity to resolve how the composition of that gas and dust impacts the star formation rate.

This image highlights the spiral galaxy’s northern half, with the galaxy’s central bulge located just outside of view at bottom left.

#NASAWebb #Hubble #UnfoldtheUniverse #galaxies

Credit: ESA/Hubble & NASA; Nick Rose.

node.text:
🌟 WEBB INTERN SPOTLIGHT: Meet Alyson Wirtz 🌟

“Hi, I’m Alyson and I’m a student at @uhmanoanews studying astronomy. I am also an intern at NASA working on a research project for the James Webb Space Telescope. The project that I am working on is focused on early galaxies that formed after the Big Bang occurred.

Being accepted to be a part of this team is something I have dreamed about for my whole life and the reality of it is so much better than I could have ever imagined. What I feel helped me get this internship position was being really honest with the people who interviewed me by telling them how passionate I was about space exploration. I believe they could really tell how much it meant to me and how determined I was to be successful.

When I finally got accepted and started to work, I’ve made every attempt to reach out and make connections along the way. I believe networking is very important and in doing so you get to make many more great memories. So far, my favorite memory has been seeing the Webb telescope in person. This has really given me a complete overall experience since we have been virtual this whole time. I encourage all of you to follow your passions and to never give up on your dreams because anything is possible. In my free time I love being in nature, traveling, and stargazing.”

node.text:
🌟 WEBB INTERN SPOTLIGHT: Meet Lindsey Jacobson 🌟

“My name is Lindsey Jacobson, and I'm a rising senior at @ncstate studying Aerospace Engineering with a minor in Industrial Engineering. Last summer, I reviewed the risk management process for Webb to determine and document why each technical risk was accepted. I also suggested further actions that could be taken to provide greater confidence in mission success. This summer, I am creating a preliminary risk assessment for future space telescope concepts based on lessons learned from the design and development of Webb.
 
I wanted to work for NASA since I was a freshman in high school. I originally wanted to be an Astrophysicist after being inspired by the @NASAHubble images we studied in environmental science. Later, I became interested in Aerospace Engineering when I toured @nasakennedy and learned how the concept of the space shuttle was developed. It was at that point that I really saw the beauty in engineering design. I am really grateful that I’ve been able to work with Webb because it has allowed me to combine my passion for engineering design with my love of astrophysics.
 
For anyone who is interested in pursuing a NASA internship, my best advice would be to just go for it. NASA has so many opportunities to get involved with projects across all disciplines. Find the opportunities that you're most interested in, apply early, and reach out to internship mentors and coordinators if you can. Don't stop putting yourself out there once you get the internship either. Some of the most meaningful conversations I've had at NASA have stemmed from sending cold emails to engineers working on projects that I'm interested in. The workplace culture at NASA is so supportive and welcoming. The internship is really what you make of it!”
